{
  "A combustion reaction always requires which gas as a reactant?": "",
  "Carbon dioxide (CO₂)": "",
  "Hydrogen (H₂)": "",
  "Oxygen (O₂)": "",
  "Nitrogen (N₂)": "",
  "By definition, combustion is the rapid reaction of a substance with oxygen. Without O₂, combustion cannot occur.": "",
  "Complete combustion of a hydrocarbon produces:": "",
  "CO₂ and H₂": "",
  "CO and H₂O": "",
  "C and H₂O": "",
  "CO₂ and H₂O": "",
  "When a hydrocarbon burns in excess oxygen, all carbon is converted to CO₂ and all hydrogen to H₂O — these are the only products of complete combustion.": "",
  "Incomplete combustion occurs when there is:": "",
  "Insufficient oxygen": "",
  "Too much fuel": "",
  "No fuel present": "",
  "Excess oxygen": "",
  "When the oxygen supply is limited, the fuel cannot burn completely. This produces CO (carbon monoxide) or soot (C) instead of CO₂.": "",
  "Products of incomplete combustion include:": "",
  "Only CO₂ and H₂O": "",
  "Carbon monoxide (CO) or soot (C)": "",
  "Nitrogen oxides only": "",
  "Noble gases": "",
  "With insufficient O₂, not all carbon is fully oxidized to CO₂. Instead, toxic CO or solid carbon (soot) forms.": "",
  "Combustion reactions are always:": "",
  "Exothermic (release energy)": "",
  "Neither exo- nor endothermic": "",
  "Endothermic (absorb energy)": "",
  "Always slow": "",
  "Combustion releases energy as heat and light, making it exothermic. This energy release is why fossil fuels are used for power.": "",
  "Which equation represents a combustion reaction?": "",
  "AgNO₃ + NaCl → AgCl + NaNO₃": "",
  "NaCl → Na + Cl₂": "",
  "Zn + CuSO₄ → ZnSO₄ + Cu": "",
  "CH₄ + 2O₂ → CO₂ + 2H₂O": "",
  "CH₄ (methane, a hydrocarbon) reacting with O₂ to produce CO₂ and H₂O is a classic combustion reaction. The other options are decomposition, double replacement, and single replacement.": "",
  "The primary fuel in a combustion reaction is usually:": "",
  "A hydrocarbon or organic compound": "",
  "A metal oxide": "",
  "Pure oxygen": "",
  "A noble gas": "",
  "Fuels like methane (CH₄), propane (C₃H₈), and octane (C₈H₁₈) are hydrocarbons. Organic compounds containing C and H readily undergo combustion.": "",
  "What phase is water in immediately after a high-temperature combustion?": "",
  "Solid (ice)": "",
  "Gas (steam/vapor)": "",
  "Plasma": "",
  "Liquid": "",
  "At the high temperatures produced by combustion, water exists as steam (gaseous H₂O). It may condense to liquid as it cools.": "",
  "Why is carbon monoxide (CO) from incomplete combustion dangerous?": "",
  "It is a colorless, odorless toxic gas that binds to hemoglobin": "",
  "It causes explosions on contact with water": "",
  "It is a strong acid": "",
  "It is radioactive": "",
  "CO binds to hemoglobin ~200× more tightly than O₂, blocking oxygen transport in the blood. Because CO is colorless and odorless, victims may not notice exposure.": "",
  "What distinguishes complete from incomplete combustion?": "",
  "Complete occurs at lower temperatures": "",
  "Complete has sufficient O₂ giving CO₂ and H₂O; incomplete has limited O₂ giving CO or C": "",
  "Incomplete always produces NO₂": "",
  "There is no real difference": "",
  "The key variable is oxygen supply. Excess O₂ leads to complete combustion (CO₂ + H₂O). Limited O₂ leads to incomplete combustion with CO, C, or both.": "",
  "What does the term 'hydrocarbon' mean?": "",
  "A compound containing carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen": "",
  "A compound composed only of carbon and hydrogen atoms": "",
  "Any compound containing water": "",
  "A mixture of hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide": "",
  "Hydrocarbons contain only H and C (e.g., CH₄, C₂H₆, C₈H₁₈). Compounds that also contain O, N, or other elements are not pure hydrocarbons.": "",
  "What is meant by 'exothermic' in the context of combustion?": "",
  "The products weigh more than the reactants": "",
  "The reaction absorbs heat from the surroundings": "",
  "The reaction occurs at constant temperature": "",
  "The reaction releases energy to the surroundings as heat and light": "",
  "Exothermic ('exo' = out, 'thermic' = heat) means the reaction releases energy. Combustion is strongly exothermic, which is why burning fuels heats surroundings.": "",
  "Define 'fuel' in chemistry.": "",
  "Any substance that is liquid at room temperature": "",
  "An element found in Group 1 of the periodic table": "",
  "A substance that undergoes combustion to release usable energy": "",
  "A catalyst for industrial reactions": "",
  "A fuel is a material that stores chemical energy and releases it via combustion. Common fuels include natural gas (CH₄), propane, gasoline, and wood.": "",
  "What is 'soot'?": "",
  "An allotrope of oxygen": "",
  "Water vapor from complete combustion": "",
  "A type of catalyst": "",
  "Solid carbon particles produced by incomplete combustion": "",
  "Soot is finely divided carbon (C) that results when there is insufficient oxygen to convert all carbon to CO₂ during combustion.": "",
  "What does 'complete combustion' specifically require?": "",
  "High pressure only": "",
  "Sufficient (excess) oxygen to fully oxidize the fuel": "",
  "The absence of any nitrogen": "",
  "A metal catalyst": "",
  "Complete combustion means every carbon becomes CO₂ and every hydrogen becomes H₂O. This only happens when enough O₂ is present for full oxidation.": "",
  "What does the general equation CₓHᵧ + O₂ → CO₂ + H₂O represent?": "",
  "Single replacement in organic chemistry": "",
  "Decomposition of a hydrocarbon": "",
  "Complete combustion of a hydrocarbon": "",
  "Synthesis of a hydrocarbon": "",
  "This is the general template for complete combustion: a hydrocarbon plus excess oxygen yields carbon dioxide and water.": "",
  "What is 'activation energy' in the context of starting a fire?": "",
  "The minimum energy needed to initiate the combustion reaction": "",
  "The temperature of the products": "",
  "The total energy released by the fire": "",
  "The mass of fuel required": "",
  "A spark or match provides the activation energy to start combustion. Once the reaction begins, it releases enough heat to sustain itself.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'ignition temperature'?": "",
  "The maximum temperature a flame can reach": "",
  "The minimum temperature at which a fuel begins to burn in air": "",
  "The boiling point of the fuel": "",
  "The temperature at which oxygen liquefies": "",
  "Ignition temperature is the threshold temperature at which a substance begins sustained combustion without needing a continued external heat source.": "",
  "Define 'incomplete combustion' in your own scientific terms.": "",
  "Burning with insufficient O₂, yielding CO, C (soot), or both instead of only CO₂": "",
  "Burning that produces no heat": "",
  "A reaction that never finishes": "",
  "A reaction where the fuel is left over": "",
  "Incomplete combustion happens when O₂ is limited. Carbon is only partially oxidized, producing toxic CO or solid soot rather than harmless CO₂.": "",
  "What does 'flammable' mean?": "",
  "Reacts only with acids": "",
  "Easily ignited and capable of burning rapidly": "",
  "Unable to catch fire": "",
  "Dissolves in water": "",
  "Flammable substances have low ignition temperatures and readily undergo combustion when exposed to a spark or flame in the presence of oxygen.": "",
  "A gas stove has a yellow, sooty flame instead of a blue flame. What does this indicate?": "",
  "Complete combustion is occurring": "",
  "The gas is of higher quality": "",
  "The stove is overheating": "",
  "Incomplete combustion due to insufficient air supply": "",
  "A yellow, sooty flame means the gas isn't getting enough O₂ for complete combustion. Soot (carbon particles) glows yellow. A blue flame indicates complete combustion.": "",
  "A CO detector alarm goes off in a home with a gas furnace. What is likely happening?": "",
  "Complete combustion is occurring normally": "",
  "The furnace is undergoing incomplete combustion, producing carbon monoxide": "",
  "The furnace is producing too much CO₂": "",
  "The detector is sensing water vapor": "",
  "CO detectors sense carbon monoxide. If CO is accumulating, the furnace's air intake is likely restricted, causing incomplete combustion and producing toxic CO instead of CO₂.": "",
  "Propane (C₃H₈) is burned in a camping stove. How many moles of O₂ are needed for complete combustion of 1 mole of propane? C₃H₈ + 5O₂ → 3CO₂ + 4H₂O": "",
  "5 moles O₂": "",
  "4 moles O₂": "",
  "3 moles O₂": "",
  "8 moles O₂": "",
  "The balanced equation shows a 1:5 mole ratio of C₃H₈ to O₂. One mole of propane requires five moles of oxygen for complete combustion.": "",
  "A candle burns in a sealed jar and eventually goes out. Why?": "",
  "The oxygen in the jar is consumed, stopping combustion": "",
  "The wax becomes too cold to melt": "",
  "CO₂ is flammable and extinguishes the flame": "",
  "The jar absorbs all the heat": "",
  "Combustion requires a continuous supply of O₂. In a sealed jar, the oxygen is used up and replaced by CO₂ and H₂O, so the flame cannot continue.": "",
  "Electric cars produce no tailpipe emissions. What does this tell you about combustion in electric vehicles?": "",
  "No combustion reaction occurs in the vehicle's motor": "",
  "They use nitrogen as fuel": "",
  "They use perfect complete combustion": "",
  "They combust water instead of gasoline": "",
  "Electric vehicles use electric motors powered by batteries — there is no combustion of fuel. Hence, there are no CO₂ or CO emissions from the vehicle itself.": "",
  "A Bunsen burner has an adjustable air hole. Opening it wider changes the flame from yellow to blue. Why?": "",
  "Closing the air hole would also give a blue flame": "",
  "The gas gets hotter but burns the same way": "",
  "More air (O₂) enters, shifting from incomplete to complete combustion": "",
  "The flame color is due to different gas types": "",
  "Opening the air hole increases O₂ supply, promoting complete combustion (blue flame). A restricted air hole limits O₂, causing incomplete combustion (yellow, sooty flame).": "",
  "Charcoal grills produce CO when the lid is closed too tightly. Explain why.": "",
  "Charcoal decomposes in the heat rather than burning": "",
  "Closing the lid increases O₂ concentration": "",
  "Restricted airflow limits O₂, causing incomplete combustion": "",
  "The lid catalyzes CO production": "",
  "Closing the lid reduces O₂ supply. With limited oxygen, carbon in the charcoal is only partially oxidized to CO instead of fully to CO₂.": "",
  "Jet fuel (kerosene) is a hydrocarbon that powers aircraft engines. What are the main products when kerosene undergoes complete combustion at altitude?": "",
  "CO and soot": "",
  "Nitrogen gas and water": "",
  "Ozone and hydrogen": "",
  "Kerosene is a hydrocarbon. Complete combustion in a jet engine (with excess O₂) produces CO₂ and H₂O, same as any hydrocarbon combustion.": "",
  "A survivalist lights a fire in a cave. The fire starts well but flames become small and orange. What should the survivalist do?": "",
  "Add more fuel to make the fire bigger": "",
  "Pour water on the fire and restart": "",
  "Seal the cave entrance to contain heat": "",
  "Increase ventilation to provide more O₂ for complete combustion": "",
  "The orange flame indicates incomplete combustion (low O₂). Improving ventilation brings in fresh air, supplying more O₂ and shifting toward complete, efficient combustion.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher burns magnesium ribbon in air: 2Mg + O₂ → 2MgO. Is this a combustion reaction even though Mg is not a hydrocarbon?": "",
  "No — only hydrocarbons can undergo combustion": "",
  "No — this is a synthesis reaction only": "",
  "Yes — any rapid reaction with O₂ producing heat and light is combustion": "",
  "Yes — but only because MgO is a gas": "",
  "Combustion includes any vigorous reaction with O₂ that produces heat and light. Metals like Mg burn brightly in air, qualifying as combustion even though they are not hydrocarbons.": ""
